		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Russia, or the Russian Federation, is the largest country in the world stretching eleven time zones. Early Russians were called East Slavs, who emerged as a group of people around 3rd century AC. They established the medieval Russia by the 9th century and were the ancestors of Belarusians and Ukrainians as well as Russians. Mongols led by Batu Khan took over this land briefly in the 13th century. In the 14th century Grand Duchy of Russia became the head of the Eastern Roman Empire. By the 17th century, Russian Empire had become the third largest empire in the world stretching from Norway to Alaska.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://cdni.rbth.com/rbthmedia/images/2020.02/article/5e43cb6385600a39d1169ca2.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>The East Slavs established medieval Russia</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				
Towards the end of the FIrst World War in 1917 Vladimir Lenin, a Marxist activist, led the Bolshevik Party that he founded into a revolution to over throw the Tsars, which turned into a civil war. Lenin’s side won the civil war, and the communist regime took over. Russia became known as the Union of Soviet Socialist Republic-USSR. After Lenin’s death in 1924, Joseph Stalin came to power and
 
millions of Russians died in famines and his brutal executions. Russia had played a significant role in the second world war losing 20 million people.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://cdn.images.express.co.uk/img/dynamic/78/590x/Stalin-The-dictator-s-unblemished-portrait-on-the-backdrop-of-a-communist-youth-rally-Berlin-1950-1312854.jpg?r=1595421481770">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Joseph Stalin, leader of the Soviet Union</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				After USSR developed nuclear weapons in 1949, the relations between USA and USSR became strained. The isolationist policies of communist Russia made their economy weak leading to the dissolution of Soviet Union. Following the dissolution of the Union in 1991, USSR became the Russian Federation.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://www.skillsetmag.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/14/2021/03/iStock-184282094.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>The Soviet Union maintained strict isolationist and communist principles</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Today Russia is run as a federal dual-executive republic with a president and a prime minister in charge. Russia’s economy is the fifth largest in Europe relying on mostly mineral and energy resources, and is one of the worlds largest oil producers. Russia is a member of the United Nations, G20, and the Council of Europe. Russia’s capital is Moscow home to almost 13 million people, makes up about 10% of the total Russian population. Other large cities in Russia are Saint Petersburg, Yekaterinburg and Novosibirsk.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://wallpaperaccess.com/full/508402.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>St. Petersburg, Russia</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Since Russia is such a vast country, it is also home to many different geological formations such as land forms like the Caucasus Mountains, the Ural Mountains, and the Siberian Planes, and bodies of water like the Volga River, the Baltic Sea and the Black Sea. Russia is also home to the largest fresh water lake in the world: Lake Baikal. Lake Baikal reaches depths of 1600 meters (5300 ft).
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://cdn.hswstatic.com/gif/lake-baikal.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Lake Baikal in Siberia, Russia</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Russia’s climate range is cool around the Black Sea, to frigid in Siberia, with summers varying from warm to cool in the arctic regions.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://i.pinimg.com/originals/d5/1d/d5/d51dd510bb9af862833f4b0056155538.jpg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Siberia, Russia</figcaption></em>
				</span>
			</figure>
		</div>
		
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Russia is known for its unique architecture. St Basil’s Cathedral in Red Square, Moscow is one of the most visited landmarks. St Basil’s Cathedral was built in 1555, however the iconic colors weren’t painted for 200 years after it was built!

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
